1
00:01:00,103 --> 00:01:02,105
[BANGING]

2
00:01:04,399 --> 00:01:06,109
What the fuck is that?

3
00:01:06,818 --> 00:01:07,986
Jimmy?

4
00:01:08,278 --> 00:01:10,030
- What's up?
- Did I hit something?

5
00:01:10,197 --> 00:01:11,865
What the fuck is that?

6
00:01:12,908 --> 00:01:14,534
Maybe you got a flat?

7
00:01:15,410 --> 00:01:17,663
Wha--? No.

8
00:01:19,289 --> 00:01:21,250
What the fuck?
You better pull over and see.

9
00:01:26,922 --> 00:01:28,924
[BANGING]

10
00:01:46,858 --> 00:01:48,110
[STAMMERING]

11
00:01:48,402 --> 00:01:50,654
He's still alive. You fucking piece of shit!

12
00:01:50,821 --> 00:01:53,657
Die, you motherfucker! Look at me!

13
00:02:03,125 --> 00:02:07,087
HENRY: <i>As far back as I can remember,
I always wanted to be a gangster.</i>

14
00:02:47,044 --> 00:02:48,086
<i>To me...</i>

15
00:02:48,253 --> 00:02:52,507
<i>...being a gangster was better than
being president of the United States.</i>

16
00:02:55,802 --> 00:02:59,348
<i>Even before I first wandered
into the cabstand for an after-school job...</i>

17
00:02:59,514 --> 00:03:01,600
<i>I knew I wanted to be a part of them.</i>

18
00:03:01,767 --> 00:03:04,186
<i>It was there that I knew I belonged.</i>

19
00:03:04,353 --> 00:03:08,857
<i>To me, it meant being somebody
in a neighborhood full of nobodies.</i>

20
00:03:09,024 --> 00:03:12,110
<i>They weren't like anybody else.
They did whatever they wanted.</i>

21
00:03:12,277 --> 00:03:15,864
<i>They double-parked in front of a hydrant,
nobody ever gave them a ticket.</i>

22
00:03:16,031 --> 00:03:18,241
<i>In the summer,
when they played cards all night...</i>

23
00:03:18,408 --> 00:03:20,660
<i>...nobody ever called the cops.</i>

24
00:03:22,287 --> 00:03:24,122
[MEN CHATTERING]

25
00:03:32,839 --> 00:03:34,716
MAN:
Tony Stacks. How are you?

26
00:03:36,009 --> 00:03:37,511
HENRY:
<i>Tuddy Cicero.</i>

27
00:03:37,677 --> 00:03:39,930
Could this be the Canarsie Kid?

28
00:03:40,555 --> 00:03:42,099
- How are you?
- Good.

29
00:03:43,392 --> 00:03:44,559
HENRY:
<i>Tuddy.</i>

30
00:03:45,477 --> 00:03:48,522
<i>Tuddy ran the cabstand
and the Bella Vista Pizzeria...</i>

31
00:03:48,688 --> 00:03:53,318
<i>and other places for his brother, Paul,
who was the boss of the neighborhood.</i>

32
00:03:53,819 --> 00:03:55,821
[LAUGHING]

33
00:03:57,948 --> 00:04:00,242
<i>Paulie might have moved slow...</i>

34
00:04:02,702 --> 00:04:06,665
<i>but it was only because Paulie
didn't have to move for anybody.</i>

35
00:04:11,336 --> 00:04:12,963
- It's your fault.
- You started it.

36
00:04:13,130 --> 00:04:15,173
I started it? It's your fault.

37
00:04:15,340 --> 00:04:17,509
HENRY: <i>At first my parents loved
that I found a job...</i>

38
00:04:17,676 --> 00:04:19,761
<i>across the street from the house.</i>

39
00:04:20,887 --> 00:04:24,641
<i>My father, who was Irish,
was sent to work at the age of 11.</i>

40
00:04:24,933 --> 00:04:26,726
<i>He liked that I got myself a job.</i>

41
00:04:26,893 --> 00:04:30,439
<i>He always used to say
that American kids were spoiled lazy.</i>

42
00:04:32,232 --> 00:04:33,859
- Bye, Dad.
- Bye.

43
00:04:34,359 --> 00:04:35,652
See you, Mikey.

44
00:04:35,819 --> 00:04:37,028
Bye, Henry.

45
00:04:37,195 --> 00:04:39,364
HENRY'S MOTHER:
Henry! Watch how you cross!

46
00:04:39,531 --> 00:04:40,782
Bring back milk!

47
00:04:40,949 --> 00:04:44,077
HENRY: <i>My mother was happy after
she found out that the Ciceros...</i>

48
00:04:44,244 --> 00:04:47,789
<i>came from the same part of Sicily
as she did. To my mother...</i>

49
00:04:47,956 --> 00:04:50,750
<i>that was the answer to all her prayers.</i>

50
00:04:52,461 --> 00:04:54,671
<i>I was the luckiest kid in the world.</i>

51
00:04:54,838 --> 00:04:57,674
<i>I could go anywhere, I could do anything.</i>

52
00:04:57,841 --> 00:05:00,510
<i>I knew everybody,
and everybody knew me.</i>

53
00:05:00,969 --> 00:05:03,722
<i>Wiseguys would pull up
and Tuddy would toss me their keys...</i>

54
00:05:03,889 --> 00:05:05,640
<i>and let me park their Cadillacs.</i>

55
00:05:05,807 --> 00:05:09,394
<i>Here I am, this little kid,
I can't even see over the steering wheel...</i>

56
00:05:09,561 --> 00:05:11,730
<i>and I'm parking Cadillacs.</i>

57
00:05:14,983 --> 00:05:17,110
<i>But it wasn't too long...</i>

58
00:05:17,277 --> 00:05:21,072
<i>before my parents changed
their minds about my job at the cabstand.</i>

59
00:05:21,239 --> 00:05:22,866
For your mother and sister.

60
00:05:23,033 --> 00:05:26,411
HENRY: <i>For them, the cabstand was
supposed to be a part-time job. But for me...</i>

61
00:05:26,578 --> 00:05:28,538
<i>it was definitely full-time.</i>

62
00:05:28,705 --> 00:05:30,624
<i>That's all I wanted to do.</i>

63
00:05:30,790 --> 00:05:34,961
<i>People like my father could never
understand, but I was a part of something.</i>

64
00:05:35,128 --> 00:05:37,923
<i>I belonged. I was treated like a grown-up.</i>

65
00:05:38,757 --> 00:05:40,258
Tell him 519.

66
00:05:40,509 --> 00:05:42,427
HENRY:
<i>Every day I was learning to score.</i>

67
00:05:42,594 --> 00:05:45,096
<i>A dollar here, a dollar there.</i>

68
00:05:45,263 --> 00:05:47,182
<i>I was living in a fantasy.</i>

69
00:05:47,349 --> 00:05:49,392
[MEN CHATTERING]

70
00:05:49,726 --> 00:05:51,269
Did you have a good day at school?

71
00:05:51,436 --> 00:05:53,230
HENRY:
<i>My father was always pissed off.</i>

72
00:05:53,396 --> 00:05:55,524
<i>Pissed that he made such lousy money...</i>

73
00:05:55,690 --> 00:05:58,610
<i>pissed that my kid brother Michael
was in a wheelchair.</i>

74
00:05:58,777 --> 00:06:03,031
<i>He was pissed that there were seven of us
living in such a tiny house.</i>

75
00:06:03,448 --> 00:06:04,908
Tell me about this.

76
00:06:05,575 --> 00:06:07,619
It's a letter from school.

77
00:06:08,119 --> 00:06:10,956
It says you haven't been there in months.

78
00:06:12,207 --> 00:06:13,542
In months!

79
00:06:13,708 --> 00:06:14,876
[HENRY'S MOTHER SCREAMING]

80
00:06:15,043 --> 00:06:16,670
You're a bum!

81
00:06:16,836 --> 00:06:19,089
Want to grow up to be a bum?

82
00:06:20,632 --> 00:06:24,803
HENRY: <i>After a while, he was mostly pissed
because I hung around the cabstand.</i>

83
00:06:24,970 --> 00:06:26,846
<i>He knew what went on at that cabstand.</i>

84
00:06:27,013 --> 00:06:31,643
<i>Every once in a while, I'd have to take
a beating. But by then, I didn't care.</i>

85
00:06:31,977 --> 00:06:33,687
<i>The way I saw it...</i>

86
00:06:34,020 --> 00:06:36,648
<i>everybody takes a beating sometime.</i>

87
00:06:37,941 --> 00:06:41,861
- I can't make any more deliveries.
- What? You'll fuck everything up.

88
00:06:42,028 --> 00:06:43,947
My dad says he'll kill me. Look.

89
00:06:44,114 --> 00:06:45,407
Come on with me.

90
00:06:45,699 --> 00:06:47,617
MAN: Is that him, kid?
HENRY: No.

91
00:06:48,285 --> 00:06:49,995
- MAN: How about him?
- No.

92
00:06:51,997 --> 00:06:54,040
- That's the guy.
- Get him.

93
00:06:55,834 --> 00:06:57,168
Excuse me.

94
00:06:58,336 --> 00:07:01,006
- Scumbag.
- Come here, you piece of shit.

95
00:07:08,805 --> 00:07:10,932
- Know this kid?
- Yeah.

96
00:07:11,099 --> 00:07:12,767
- TUDDY: Know where he lives?
- Yeah.

97
00:07:12,934 --> 00:07:15,061
TUDDY: You deliver mail to his house?
MAILMAN: Yeah.

98
00:07:15,228 --> 00:07:19,065
TUDDY: From now on, any letter from that
school to his house comes directly here.

99
00:07:19,232 --> 00:07:20,525
- Understand?
- MAILMAN: Yeah.

100
00:07:20,692 --> 00:07:23,292
TUDDY: Another letter from that school
goes to that kid's house...

101
00:07:23,445 --> 00:07:25,822
in the fucking oven you'll go, head first.

102
00:07:25,989 --> 00:07:30,285
HENRY: <i>That was it. No more letters from
truant officers. No letters from school.</i>

103
00:07:30,452 --> 00:07:32,537
<i>In fact, no more letters from anybody.</i>

104
00:07:32,704 --> 00:07:36,499
<i>Finally after a few weeks, my mother
went to the post office to complain.</i>

105
00:07:36,833 --> 00:07:38,501
<i>How could I go to school after that...</i>

106
00:07:38,668 --> 00:07:42,797
<i>and pledge allegiance to the flag
and sit through good government bullshit?</i>

107
00:07:45,884 --> 00:07:49,054
<i>Paulie hated phones.
He wouldn't have one in his house.</i>

108
00:07:49,220 --> 00:07:51,890
Mickey called. Want me to call him back?

109
00:07:52,265 --> 00:07:53,892
All right, make the call.

110
00:07:54,059 --> 00:07:57,646
HENRY: <i>He got all his calls second hand.
Then you'd have to call the people back...</i>

111
00:07:57,812 --> 00:07:58,855
<i>from an outside phone.</i>

112
00:07:59,022 --> 00:08:01,483
Got a nickel? Get him on the phone.

113
00:08:02,233 --> 00:08:06,988
HENRY: <i>There were guys, that's all they did
all day, was take care of Paulie's calls.</i>

114
00:08:13,244 --> 00:08:15,580
[CHATTERING]

115
00:08:16,623 --> 00:08:20,919
<i>For a guy who moved all day long,
Paulie didn't talk to six people.</i>

116
00:08:21,086 --> 00:08:24,089
<i>If there was a union problem
or, say, a beef in the numbers...</i>

117
00:08:24,255 --> 00:08:27,759
<i>only the top guys could meet
with Paulie to discuss the problem.</i>

118
00:08:27,926 --> 00:08:31,179
<i>Everything was one-on-one.
Paulie hated conferences.</i>

119
00:08:31,930 --> 00:08:34,391
<i>He didn't want anybody
hearing what he said...</i>

120
00:08:34,557 --> 00:08:37,852
<i>and he didn't want anybody listening
to what he was being told.</i>

121
00:08:38,019 --> 00:08:42,273
<i>Hundreds of guys depended on Paulie,
he got a piece of everything they made.</i>

122
00:08:42,440 --> 00:08:46,778
<i>It was a tribute, like in the old country,
except they were doing it in America.</i>

123
00:08:46,945 --> 00:08:51,408
<i>All they got from Paulie was protection
from other guys looking to rip them off.</i>

124
00:08:51,574 --> 00:08:55,495
<i>That's what it's all about. That's what
the FBI could never understand.</i>

125
00:08:55,954 --> 00:08:58,123
<i>What Paulie and the Organization does...</i>

126
00:08:58,289 --> 00:09:02,210
<i>is offer protection for people
who can't go to the cops. That's it.</i>

127
00:09:02,794 --> 00:09:06,923
<i>That's all it is. They're like
the police department for wiseguys.</i>

128
00:09:07,132 --> 00:09:08,425
[GLASS SHATTERING]

129
00:09:16,725 --> 00:09:20,812
<i>People looked at me differently,
and they knew I was with somebody.</i>

130
00:09:20,979 --> 00:09:25,442
<i>I didn't have to wait in line at the bakery
on Sunday mornings for fresh bread.</i>

131
00:09:25,608 --> 00:09:26,888
<i>The owner knew who I was with...</i>

132
00:09:27,026 --> 00:09:30,405
<i>and he'd come from around the counter.
No matter how many were waiting...</i>

133
00:09:30,572 --> 00:09:32,574
<i>I was taken care of first.</i>

134
00:09:32,824 --> 00:09:35,160
<i>Our neighbors didn't park
in our driveway anymore...</i>

135
00:09:35,326 --> 00:09:38,163
<i>even though we didn't have a car.
At 13...</i>

136
00:09:38,329 --> 00:09:40,999
<i>I was making more money than most
of the grown-ups around.</i>

137
00:09:41,166 --> 00:09:44,294
<i>I had more money than I could spend.
I had it all.</i>

138
00:09:54,429 --> 00:09:59,100
<i>One day, some neighborhood kids carried
my mother's groceries all the way home.</i>

139
00:09:59,267 --> 00:10:00,685
<i>You know why?</i>

140
00:10:01,519 --> 00:10:03,354
<i>It was out of respect.</i>

141
00:10:05,106 --> 00:10:07,192
Hi, Mom, what do you think?

142
00:10:08,818 --> 00:10:11,529
- Look at my shoes, aren't they great?
- My God.

143
00:10:12,071 --> 00:10:13,698
You look like a gangster.

144
00:10:13,865 --> 00:10:15,533
They shot me. Help!

145
00:10:15,950 --> 00:10:17,994
[MAN YELLING]

146
00:10:18,161 --> 00:10:19,954
TUDDY:
Henry, shut the door.

147
00:10:20,955 --> 00:10:24,250
HENRY: <i>That was the first time
I had ever seen anyone shot.</i>

148
00:10:25,043 --> 00:10:27,462
Can't have that in here. Jesus Christ!

149
00:10:27,629 --> 00:10:29,255
I can't have that in this joint.

150
00:10:29,422 --> 00:10:31,222
HENRY:
<i>I remember feeling bad about the guy...</i>

151
00:10:31,382 --> 00:10:34,511
<i>but I also remember feeling
that maybe Tuddy was right.</i>

152
00:10:34,761 --> 00:10:37,388
<i>I knew Paulie didn't want
anybody dying in the building.</i>

153
00:10:37,555 --> 00:10:41,392
You're a real jerk. You wasted
eight fucking aprons on this guy.

154
00:10:41,559 --> 00:10:44,729
What the hell's wrong with you?
I got to toughen this kid up.

155
00:11:04,499 --> 00:11:06,417
HENRY:
<i>It was a glorious time.</i>

156
00:11:07,335 --> 00:11:09,921
<i>And wiseguys were all over the place.</i>

157
00:11:10,880 --> 00:11:13,842
<i>It was before Apalachin
and before Crazy Joe...</i>

158
00:11:14,008 --> 00:11:16,928
<i>decided to take on a boss and start a war.</i>

159
00:11:17,595 --> 00:11:19,639
<i>It was when I met the world.</i>

160
00:11:19,806 --> 00:11:22,517
<i>And it was when I first met
Jimmy Conway.</i>

161
00:11:23,977 --> 00:11:27,146
<i>He couldn't have been more than 28 or 29
at the time...</i>

162
00:11:27,313 --> 00:11:29,232
<i>but he was already a legend.</i>

163
00:11:29,399 --> 00:11:33,403
<i>He'd walk in the door and everybody
who worked the room just went wild.</i>

164
00:11:33,570 --> 00:11:36,155
<i>He'd give the doorman $100
just for opening the door.</i>

165
00:11:36,322 --> 00:11:40,243
<i>He'd give hundreds to the dealers
and the guys who ran the games.</i>

166
00:11:40,410 --> 00:11:43,371
<i>The bartender got $100
just for keeping the ice cubes cold.</i>

167
00:11:43,538 --> 00:11:46,624
The Irishman is here
to take all you guineas' money.

168
00:11:49,836 --> 00:11:52,589
- Want a drink?
- Give me a 7 and 7.

169
00:11:59,721 --> 00:12:03,099
- I'd like you to meet the kid Henry.
- How you doing?

170
00:12:05,476 --> 00:12:08,187
- Thank you.
- Keep them coming.

171
00:12:08,354 --> 00:12:11,357
HENRY: <i>Jimmy was one of the most
feared guys in the city.</i>

172
00:12:11,524 --> 00:12:13,151
<i>He was first locked up at 11...</i>

173
00:12:13,318 --> 00:12:16,404
<i>and he was doing hits
for mob bosses when he was 16.</i>

174
00:12:16,571 --> 00:12:19,365
<i>See, hits never bothered Jimmy.
It was business.</i>

175
00:12:19,824 --> 00:12:21,910
<i>But what Jimmy really loved to do...</i>

176
00:12:22,076 --> 00:12:24,120
<i>what he really loved to do was steal.</i>

177
00:12:24,287 --> 00:12:26,456
<i>He actually enjoyed it.</i>

178
00:12:26,623 --> 00:12:30,543
<i>Jimmy was the kind of guy who rooted
for the bad guys in the movies.</i>

179
00:12:31,252 --> 00:12:33,004
Give me your wallet.

180
00:12:36,007 --> 00:12:39,177
You might know who we are,
but we know who you are. Understand?

181
00:12:39,344 --> 00:12:41,721
HENRY: <i>He was one of
the city's biggest hijackers...</i>

182
00:12:41,888 --> 00:12:45,350
<i>of booze, cigarettes, razor blades,
shrimp and lobsters.</i>

183
00:12:45,516 --> 00:12:48,645
<i>Shrimp and lobsters were best.
They went really fast.</i>

184
00:12:48,811 --> 00:12:52,607
<i>Almost all of them were gimmies.
They just gave it up, no problem.</i>

185
00:12:52,774 --> 00:12:54,442
<i>They called him Jimmy the Gent.</i>

186
00:12:54,609 --> 00:12:55,735
Help the lady.

187
00:12:55,902 --> 00:12:58,196
HENRY: <i>Drivers loved him.
They used to tip him off...</i>

188
00:12:58,363 --> 00:13:01,699
<i>about the really good loads.
Of course, everybody got a piece.</i>

189
00:13:01,866 --> 00:13:03,952
WOMAN:
Thanks, I'll be back for the rest later.

190
00:13:04,118 --> 00:13:05,536
JIMMY:
Okay, see you later.

191
00:13:08,039 --> 00:13:09,707
Henry, come here.

192
00:13:10,625 --> 00:13:12,669
- Say hello to Tommy.
- How're you doing, Henry?

193
00:13:12,835 --> 00:13:14,837
You're gonna be working together, okay?

194
00:13:15,004 --> 00:13:16,714
Help him. Go ahead.

195
00:13:17,090 --> 00:13:19,384
Jimmy, you got anything good?

196
00:13:19,550 --> 00:13:23,596
HENRY: <i>And when the cops assigned a
whole army to stop Jimmy, what did he do?</i>

197
00:13:23,763 --> 00:13:24,806
JIMMY:
How're you doing?

198
00:13:24,973 --> 00:13:26,683
HENRY:
<i>He made them partners.</i>

199
00:13:26,849 --> 00:13:28,476
I'd complain, but who'd listen?

200
00:13:28,810 --> 00:13:30,450
MAN 1: One Pall Mall.
HENRY: There you go.

201
00:13:30,603 --> 00:13:32,689
- What do you need?
- MAN 2: Two Luckies.

202
00:13:32,855 --> 00:13:34,732
- TOMMY: Here you go, Henry.
- Thanks a lot.

203
00:13:34,899 --> 00:13:35,942
What do you need?

204
00:13:36,109 --> 00:13:38,736
- One Pall Mall.
- One Pall Mall, here you go.

205
00:13:38,903 --> 00:13:40,571
- What are you doing?
- It's all right.

206
00:13:40,738 --> 00:13:43,741
- You have permission from your mother?
- How many cartons you need?

207
00:13:43,908 --> 00:13:46,953
- Where'd you get the cigarettes?
- Get him out of here.

208
00:13:47,120 --> 00:13:48,746
- It's okay.
- It's not okay.

209
00:13:48,913 --> 00:13:52,291
HENRY: You don't understand.
MAN: You don't understand. Store's closed.

210
00:13:57,130 --> 00:13:58,965
- Henry got pinched.
- Where?

211
00:13:59,132 --> 00:14:00,800
By the factory, selling cigarettes.

212
00:14:00,967 --> 00:14:04,929
MAN: Henry Hill. <i>The People of</i>
<i>the State of New York vs. Henry Hill.</i>

213
00:14:05,221 --> 00:14:08,016
Docket number 704162.

214
00:14:09,100 --> 00:14:11,394
Uh, yes, sir. That's me.

215
00:14:14,188 --> 00:14:16,941
Just stand there. Now stay there.

216
00:14:23,364 --> 00:14:25,116
Counselor, proceed.

217
00:14:28,119 --> 00:14:29,746
Congratulations.

